## Abstract

Background An innovative instrument for laparoscopy using indocyanine green (ICG) allows easy detection of sentinel lymph nodes (SLNs) in lateral pelvic lymph nodes (LPLNs). Here, we investigated the safety and efficacy of lateral pelvic SLN biopsy (SLNB) using ICG fluorescence navigation in advanced lower rectal cancer and evaluated the sensitivity and specificity of this technique to predict the status of LPLN.

Results We successfully performed the surgery using fluorescence navigation. One patient underwent bilateral LLND and

Methods From April 1, 2017 to December 1, 2020, we conducted lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation during laparoscopic total mesorectal excision and lateral pelvic lymph node dissection (LLND) in 23 patients with advanced low rectal cancer who presented with LPLN but without LPLN enlargement. Data regarding clinical characteristics, surgical and pathological outcomes, lymph node findings, and postoperative complications were collected and analyzed.

22 patients underwent unilateral LLND. The lateral pelvic SLN were clearly fluorescent before dissection in 21 patients. Lateral pelvic SLN metastasis was diagnosed in 3 patients and negative in 18 patients by frozen pathological examination. Among the 21 patients in whom lateral pelvic SLN was detected, the dissected lateral pelvic non-SLNs were all negative. All dissected LPLNs were negative in two patients without fluorescent lateral pelvic SLN.

Conclusion This study indicated that lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation shows promise as a safe and feasible procedure for advanced lower rectal cancer with good accuracy, and no false-negative cases were found. No metastasis in SLNB seemed to reflect all negative LPLN metastases, and this technique can replace preventive LLND for advanced lower rectal cancer.

Surgery remains the standard treatment for colorectal cancer with curative intent. Total mesorectal excision (TME) is the standard surgical procedure [1]. However, patients with advanced lower rectal cancer at or below the peritoneal reflection occasionally develop metastases to the lateral pelvic lymph nodes (LPLNs), which are considered a major site for postoperative local recurrence [2, 3]. Patients with LPLN metastasis present a particular challenge for both diagnosis and treatment. In Eastern countries, principally in Japan, LPLN metastasis is considered a local disease and is treated with lateral pelvic lymph node dissection (LLND) in addition to TME [4]. The potential surgical risks and morbidity associated with LLND, as well as the uncertainty of oncological outcomes, have made LLND controversial and limited, especially in patients with pathologically negative LPLN [5]. Preoperative radiological examinations have helped detect LPLN metastasis in 14%-20% of cases with locally advanced low rectal cancer on initial assessment, but these remain insufficient, and some patients with LPLN metastasis cannot be detected [6].

The sentinel lymph node (SLN) is the first lymph node to receive lymphatic flow from the tumor. SLN biopsy (SLNB) has been widely performed in breast cancer, malignant melanoma, and some gastrointestinal cancers [7-9]. SLN navigation surgery using indocyanine green (ICG) for gastric cancer has the potential to improve patient treatment selection [10]. ICG is a sterile, anionic, and water-soluble solution that acts as a fluorophore in response to near-infrared (NIR) irradiation and is considered an ideal agent for the acquisition of high-quality images of both the circulatory and lymphatic systems [11]. Therefore, to address these concerns, we attempted to use this innovative technique in surgery for patients who presented with advanced lower rectal cancer with LPLN but without LPLN enlargement based on magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) evaluation (i.e., lymph nodes with a short-axis diameter < 10/uni00A0mm, as seen on MR images, are not regarded as lymph node enlargement) and evaluated the sensitivity and specificity of lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation for the accurate diagnosis of LPLN metastasis. In this article, we described this technique and investigated its safety and efficacy.

## Methods

## Patients

From April 1, 2017 to December 1, 2020, consecutive patients diagnosed with advanced lower rectal cancer who underwent lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation during laparoscopic TME and LLND by a single surgeon in our hospital were enrolled retrospectively.

Eligible patients were 18-80/uni00A0years of age, with a body mass index (BMI) between 18.5 and 30/uni00A0kg/m 2 , a pathological diagnosis of rectal adenocarcinoma, and a tumor at or below the peritoneal reflection, diagnosed with stage II or III preoperatively according to the UICC-TNM classification, and presented with LPLN but without LPLN enlargement based on MRI evaluation. Patients with a history of colorectal surgery, multiple primary colorectal carcinomas, and distant metastases were excluded. Moreover, those with allergic hypersensitivity to ICG were excluded. In principle, all patients received neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy (NACRT) or neoadjuvant chemotherapy (NACT) in principle. Patients who received neoadjuvant therapy underwent surgery 6-8/uni00A0weeks after radiotherapy or 4/uni00A0weeks after chemotherapy. This study was conducted in accordance with the principles of the Declaration of Helsinki. All patients received a detailed explanation of the procedures and provided informed consent, and this study was approved by the institutional review board.

The LPLN, including the internal iliac, external iliac, and obturator nodes, was evaluated independently by the surgeon and the radiologist before surgery. The LPLN was considered present based on the maximum short axis of the LPLN /uni2265 5/uni00A0mm and enlarged based on the maximum short axis of the LPLN /uni2265 10/uni00A0mm before neoadjuvant treatment or before surgery (if the patient did not receive neoadjuvant treatment).

## Surgical procedures

The fluorescence system used in this study was an OptoCam 2100 (OptoMedic, Guangdong, China). This device can be used in standard laparoscopic visible imaging mode and can be switched to NIR fluorescence mode by means of button control on the camera head, on the stack console, or via the foot pedal.

Under general anesthesia, all patients were placed in a supine lithotomy position with a 15° tilt toward the left and the head bent downward. Then, the five-port technique was used for abdominal performance: a 10-mm supra-umbilical port was used as the observation port, a 12-mm port in the right lower quadrant was used as the primary operating port, and three 5-mm ports in the right upper quadrant, left upper quadrant, and left lower quadrant were used as the secondary operating ports. After confirming the absence of abdominal metastasis, the perineal performance was started with finger dilatation, followed by the application of an anal dilator to clearly observe the lower margin of the tumor. ICG (25/uni00A0mg; Eisai, Tokyo, JP) was diluted with 10/uni00A0mL of distilled water. Approximately 0.5/uni00A0mL of the prepared solution, containing 1.25/uni00A0mg of ICG, was injected into the submucosal layer of the rectum at three points around the primary tumor, for a total volume of 1.5/uni00A0mL (Fig./uni00A01).

First, lateral pelvic SLNB was started using ICG fluorescence navigation (Fig./uni00A02). The direction of the lateral lymph node drainage was determined through overall scanning under the guidance of ICG-enhanced NIR fluorescenceguided imaging (Fig./uni00A03A), and the first LPLN or the LPLNs receiving ICG that had a shining fluorescent spot in the image as an SLN were defined. All SLNs were resected if they were discovered and sent separately for frozen

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

pathological examination. Following the TME principle, the rectum and mesorectum were dissected, and the pelvic autonomic nerves were protected carefully.

After completion of the laparoscopic TME, the remaining LLND using ICG fluorescence navigation was performed as follows. First, a dissection was made along the ureter-hypogastric fascia close to the bladder to reveal the lateral pelvic region, and the ureters and hypogastric nerve were protected carefully. The peritoneum was opened along the edge of the external iliac vessels close to the deep inguinal ring (Fig./uni00A03B). The fatty tissue outside the external iliac vessels was removed along the edge of the iliopsoas and internal obturator muscle. Second, after identification of the obturator nerve, a dissection was made along the vesicohypogastric fascia to separate the fatty tissue around the bladder and lateral pelvic space (Fig./uni00A03C). The common internal iliac vessels and obturator nerve were completely cleared from the lymphatic tissue down to the inferior vesical vessels and obturator fossa. Third, a fluorescence system was used to observe the residual soft tissues of the lateral pelvic region to prevent the omission of lymph nodes during dissection (Fig./uni00A03D). All dissected specimens, including the SLN, were subjected to paraffin pathological examination.

## Perioperative management

From 2 to 6 PM on the day before surgery, 70/uni00A0mg of polyethylene glycol (macrogol) per 1 L of water was administered to all patients four times (1 L each hour). Preventive antibiotics were administered by intravenous drip 30/uni00A0min preoperatively and on the first day postoperatively. All patients were administered nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs intravenously. Oral intake was initiated in the first postoperative morning.

## Evaluations

The clinical characteristics collected included the patient's age, sex, BMI, American Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) score, tumor location, previous abdominal operation history, and preoperative therapy. Surgical outcomes included operative time, estimated blood loss, and type of operation. The resected specimens were reviewed by two pathologists, and the pathological outcomes included the resection margin, tumor size, and pathological TNM stage. The lymph nodes included navigation visibility, fluorescence findings, and number of harvested lymph nodes and metastatic lymph nodes. Data on postoperative complications, including anastomotic leak, lymphatic leak, anastomotic stenosis, bleeding, urinary retention, bowel obstruction, incisional infection, and ICG allergy were also collected. Reoperation and readmission rates were also measured.

## Follow-up

The first postoperative day marked the beginning of the follow-up period. After discharge, doctors contacted patients via telephone or outpatient services to evaluate the tumor state. Patients were routinely followed up at outpatient clinics 2/uni00A0weeks after discharge and every 3/uni00A0months after the operation. No patient was lost during follow-up, and the deadline of the follow-up period was March 1, 2022.

## Statistical analysis

Statistical analysis was performed using the SPSS software version 20.0 for Windows (SPSS Inc., Chicago, IL, USA). Quantitative variables are presented as means and standard deviations and qualitative data as numbers and percentages. Quantitative variables were compared using the Student t

## Results

## General data

Laparoscopic TME and LLND using ICG fluorescence navigation were successfully performed in 23 patients with advanced lower rectal cancer. During surgery, 2 patients had no identified lateral pelvic SLN which had a shining fluorescent spot in the image, therefore 21 patients underwent lateral pelvic SLNB. The patients included 15 men (65.2%) and 8 women (34.8%). Five patients (21.7%) had a history of abdominal surgery; however, none of the surgeries were converted to open surgery. The patients' mean age was 58.0/uni00A0years (range 3.6.0-76.0/uni00A0years) and mean BMI was 23.6/uni00A0kg/m 2 (range 18.0-29.4/uni00A0kg/m 2 ). A total of 16 (69.6%),

## Surgical and/uni00A0pathological outcomes

Nineteen patients (82.6%) underwent laparoscopic low anterior resection, and four patients (17.4%) underwent laparoscopic abdominoperineal resection. One patient (4.3%) underwent bilateral LLND and 22 patients (95.7%) underwent unilateral LLND. The mean time required for the surgery was 257.6/uni00A0min (range 180.0-335.0/uni00A0min) and the mean estimated intraoperative blood loss was 174.5/uni00A0mL (range 50.0-270.0/uni00A0mL). The mean time and blood loss for LLND were 98.4/uni00A0min (range 59.4-200.0/uni00A0min) and 71.8/uni00A0mL (range 30.0-115.0/uni00A0mL), respectively. Pathological diagnosis revealed a negative resection margin in all patients. The length of the tumor presented the tumor size, and the mean length was 3.2/uni00A0cm (range 1.2-6.5/uni00A0cm). The pathological stages of TNM are provided in Table/uni00A02.

## Lymph node findings

Lateral pelvic SLNs were successfully identified in 21 (76.2%) patients, and the mean time from injection to when fluorescence of the lateral pelvic SLN could be observed was 9.1/uni00A0min (range 4.0-19.0/uni00A0min) after ICG injection. Two patients had no fluorescence in the lateral pelvic lymph nodes throughout the surgery. Among the different LPLN locations, the most commonly detected lateral pelvic SLN was the obturator region.

## Postoperative complications

The mean time of postoperative hospitalization was 7/uni00A0days (range 4-13/uni00A0days), and the mean hospitalization cost was 46,917.2 CNY (range 40,022.0-55,657.0 CNY) (Table/uni00A02). During follow-up, one patient (4.3%) experienced anastomotic leakage on postoperative day 6 and recovered after transverse colostomy. One patient (4.3%) had lymphatic leakage, which was cured by fasting and adequate drainage. One patient (4.3%) had urinary retention that was replaced with a catheter for a month. No side effects or allergic reactions related to the ICG injections were observed. None of the patients experienced symptoms that were indicative of anastomotic stenosis, incisional infection, or bowel obstruction. No patient was lost to follow-up and experienced recurrence during the follow-up period. All complications were resolved successfully.

## Discussion

Substantial evidence has shown that the development of comprehensive therapy for rectal cancer, including chemotherapy, radiotherapy, immunotherapy, targeted therapy, and surgery, improved the prognosis and survival of patients with rectal cancer. However, it has been reported that the local recurrence rate of rectal cancer is as high as 21-46% [12], which has become a challenging issue in the treatment of rectal cancer. Among them, local recurrence caused by LPLN metastasis is of concern, with rates ranging from 10.6 to 25.5% [13-15]. Usually, treatment for clinical stage II or III locally advanced rectal cancer includes NACRT followed

by TME and postoperative adjuvant chemotherapy with fluorouracil and oxaliplatin. However, recent studies have shown that TME and NACRT may not adequately address the management of LPLN metastasis [16, 17]. Therefore, in Eastern countries, it is suggested that LPLN metastasis should be treated with LLND in addition to TME. However, LLND is relatively difficult due to increased surgical time, blood loss, and a higher risk of urinary and sexual dysfunction.

Yasui et/uni00A0al. [22] used ICG method to detect SLN in laparoscopic rectal cancer surgery and found that laparoscopic ICG-guided SLN strategy may be a low-risk and time-saving method to prevent laparoscopic LLND in cases with

It has been reported that ICG-enhanced NIR fluorescence-guided imaging is a feasible and convenient technique to assist LLND, and this novel technique can make the surgery much easier and shorten the learning curve for surgeons who are not familiar with LLND [18]. The ICG fluorescence technique has been used to identify vessels and lymph nodes in digestive surgery for several years. Ryu et/uni00A0al. [19] found that fluorescence navigation of the ureter is feasible in laparoscopic LLND and has the potential to increase safety. Moreover, SLN fluorescence navigation surgery has been performed for gastric cancer to detect SLN by injecting ICG around the tumor and finding lymph nodes with the earliest tracer spreading. SLN fluorescence navigation for early gastric cancer has shown acceptable SN detection rates and accuracy of lymph node status determination. Kim et/uni00A0al. [20] used the ICG fluorescent method for SLN detection in early gastric cancer and found that using the near-infrared ICG method, the sensitivity was 98.9%, the specificity was 76.0%, and the false-positive rate was 25.4%. Okubo et. al [21]. also believed that the evaluation of fluorescence intensity is useful for selected SLNs, and if fluorescence intensity is measurable in surgery, an infrared fluorescence method using ICG may be useful and safe for the detection of SLN in early gastric cancer. Therefore, the SLN fluorescence navigation method may revolutionize SLN mapping procedures in gastric cancer. Moreover, the distribution and pathological status of SLN would be useful in determining the extent of gastric resection.

negative lateral pelvic lymph nodes. But in their study, they did not include the patients after NCRT. In fact, the fluorescent presentation of lymph nodes in patients after NCRT was different from those without NCRT. They enrolled patients only without LPLN enlargement (the maximum short axis of the LPLN < 10/uni00A0mm). But for patients without LPLN presentation (the maximum short axis of the LPLN < 5/uni00A0mm), the metastasis rate was very low and LLND was considered overtreatment [23]. They performed TME at first and then completed SLNB and LLND. The long time between the injection of ICG and SLNB may affect the detection of SLN and the lymph nodes receiving ICG that had a shining fluorescent spot may be not limited to the first lymph node to receive lymphatic flow from the tumor. Moreover, frozen pathological examination of SLN was important procedure in SLNB, but they did not perform it.

The mean number of LPLN harvested in this study was 10.2 (range 5-18), which is significantly higher than that of conventional LLND and is thought to improve the intraoperative surgical staging and ultimately lead to a better oncological outcome [24]. Finally, a lateral pelvic SLN was identified in 21 (91.3%) patients, which suggests that fluorescence-guided imaging can provide better sensitivity for LLND, in which many people may benefit from. Moreover, among the 21 patients with pelvic lateral SLN detected, 3

Based on these studies, lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation was applied in patients who presented with advanced lower rectal cancer with LPLN but without LPLN enlargement and received NCRT in principle. Different from previous study, we performed lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation at first in the surgical procedures and the resected SLN were sent for frozen pathological examination. Some studies have found that ICG-enhanced NIR fluorescence-guided imaging helped decrease intraoperative blood loss and increased the number of LPLNs harvested [18]. Although no significant difference was found in the operative time compared to that of patients without fluorescence-guided imaging, it is believed that fluorescence-guided imaging can help the surgeon distinguish lymph nodes from non-lymphatic soft tissues to protect the vessels and nerves. In the present study, the mean time required for the surgery was 257.6/uni00A0min (range 180.0-335.0/uni00A0min), which is significantly shorter than the time of conventional LLND reported before, and this difference was attributed to the fast and accurate judgment of LPLN. Moreover, in this study, it did not take much time from ICG injection to fluorescence detection. Therefore, we believe that the overall operation time was not prolonged due to the injection of ICG, which conversely shortened the total time due to the quick detection of the resection zone. In fact, during LLND, we found that fluorescence-guided imaging was easy to implement with a short learning curve due to the simplicity of the LPLN detection.

patients exhibited metastasis in the pelvic lateral SLN and 18 patients were metastasis negative. In addition, all dissected LPLNs of the 18 patients with metastasis-negative lateral pelvic SLNs were negative. Therefore, the false-negative rate of pelvic lateral SLNB was 0, and the negative predictive value of the pelvic lateral SLN fluorescence navigation was 100% (18/18) in this group of patients. Meanwhile, of the 20 patients with no metastasis in the LPLN, all 20 patients showed no metastasis in the lateral pelvic SLN (including 2 patients with no lateral pelvic SLN). Therefore, the negative specificity of the lateral pelvic SLN fluorescence navigation was 100% (20/20). Moreover, the paraffin pathological results of the lateral pelvic SLN were the same as those of the frozen pathological examination. As a consequence, we believe that lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation could replace LLND in patients with advanced rectal cancer with LPLN but without LPLN enlargement. In those without metastasis in lateral pelvic SLNB using fluorescence navigation, LLND may not be necessary.

This study had several limitations. First, this was a retrospective study based on preliminary results, and the present outcomes were from a single surgeon and a relatively small number of patients. Prospective randomized controlled trials from multiple centers with larger sample sizes and longer follow-up periods are required to confirm our results. Second, postoperative survival data were not analyzed, and further long-term oncological outcomes are required to determine the actual impact of lateral pelvic SLN fluorescence navigation in laparoscopic LLND.

The reported incidence of urinary dysfunction ranges from 11 to 50%, and the risk of sexual dysfunction is 16% and 40% in conventional LLND [25]. With the increasing use of laparoscopic, robotic, and transanal robotic equipment in LLND, we attempted to refine this surgical technique. However, whether any of these developments will lead to a reduction in morbidity remains to be proven. The protective value of fluorescence-guided imaging of the ureter and nerves has been demonstrated in several studies. Kim et. al [26] believed that fluorescence-guided imaging can provide an exact understanding of the LPLN position in LLND, reduce the possibility of incomplete resection of metastatic LPLN, and avoid unnecessary injury to other neurovascular structures. We also found that only one patient had lymphatic leakage, and only one patient had urinary dysfunction. Both of the patients were treated conservatively. Side effects or allergic reactions related to ICG injection during or after surgery were not observed.

In conclusion, our results suggest that ICG fluorescence navigation can provide clear visualization of the LPLN and no metastasis in SLNB may reflect all negative LPLN metastases. The simplicity and safety of this method led us to believe that lateral pelvic SLNB using ICG fluorescence navigation would be an ideal technique for selected

advanced rectal cancer patients presenting with LPLN but without LPLN enlargement. However, further studies with long-term follow-up are required to confirm the efficacy of this technique in patients with lateral pelvic SLNB.
